<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-032-337 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 406 199</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Oct 16 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Japanese school teacher computer illiteracy reported. (Ministry ofEducation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Miyazawa, Masayuki.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government AgencyReportsTeacher EducationComputersJapan. Ministry of Education.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Japanese School Teacher Computer Illiteracy Reported 10/16/91 TOKYO, JAPAN,1991 OCT 16 (NB) -- Japan is a high tech nation, but it is behind as far ascomputer education is concerned, according to a recently released report oncomputer education in Japan's public schools, released by the JapaneseMinistry of Education.andM;According to the report, 14 out of 15 teachers cannot teach how to operatethe personal computers which are installed at their schools.andM;The report says 56.6 percent of public school have personal computers.andP;  Thefigures are 41 percent for elementary schools, 74.7 percent for Junior HighSchools and 98.5 percent for Senior High Schools.andM;However, 79.7 percent of the teachers cannot handle the machines and only 6.6percent of the teachers can instruct how to operate computers.andP;  This isconsidered something of a problem as the Education Ministry is planning tointroduce a curriculum on personal computers within three years.andP;  TheMinistry wants to hold seminars and workshops to train teachers on the use ofcomputers.andM;The ratio of personal computers installed at schools is actually not thatmany.andP;  On average, there are only 3.3 units per elementary school, 8.3 unitsper Junior High School and 35.3 units per Senior High School.andM;(Masayuki Miyazawa/19911016)</TEXT></DOC>